	<!-- message -->
	<p>Very good article, thanks.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Meanwhile, Microsoft doesn’t evoke passion in me anymore. Its products don’t excite me anymore.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I am definitely in the same boat, after having used Windows exclusively for over a decade. More and more, I'm finding that alternatives to Microsoft software are interesting, engaging, and fun to use. New projects and features spring up all the time, and on any given day I can receive multiple updates and improvements to the programs I use regularly. I do keep a copy of Windows around for the occasional game, but I never actually <i>use</i> Windows at home now for anything important - I find it sorely lacking in features and flexibility. In time, my reliance on Windows for games will also disappear and I will end up using it only when I have to deal with it at work. And if I were to ever buy a consumer PC, I would choose a Mac in a heartbeat over any Windows machine.<br />
<br />
While Microsoft isn't feeling it in the pocketbook yet, I feel quite strongly that they are starting to fall behind in a technological sense. Longhorn better be the groundbreaking product that Microsoft is claiming it to be, and even if it is, Microsoft will still have difficulty convincing customers that an upgrade is in order.</p>
	
	
	
