	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>J'horra</b><br /><i>I would probably have already switched to linux exclusively except for the lack of programs.  Till companies start writing programs for it though, I'll probably be mainly a MS person.  Never, ever will I go back to a Mac.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>*scratches head*<br />
<br />
Like what? Sure, there are some niche programs that don't exist for Linux yet, and some of the Windows or Mac alternatives are better for the top 1% of extreme power users who actually need the advanced features of, say, Illustrator or Office, but apart from games, what are you missing? I actually find the variety of software far greater for the operating system I use than I ever had available while using Windows - or at least, I couldn't spend $20-$50 a pop to try out every program I could have made use of. For daily use, I really don't see that any programs are missing for platforms other than Windows.<br />
<br />
And what's wrong with Mac? It has tens of thousands of programs available: they're called GNU. <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /> <img src="images/smilies/tongue.gif" border="0" alt="" title="stick out tongue" smilieid="6" /></p>
	
	
	
