	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>Errr...what else is there?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Many games run on Linux. In the coming years, they probably all will. And now that ATI finally got around to providing true Linux driver support, I'm looking forward to playing games natively without WineX or any other type of hack. <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /><br />
<br />
Besides, games aren't all there is to computers by a longshot. Indeed, people who use their computers exclusively for games (or even for games at all) are the great minority.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>Tons of shareware/freeware for windows too, Kirec, and half the stuff that isn't supposed to be freeware still ends up being freeware (like Windows itself!)</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Evil!<br />
<br />
My perception of the variety of software available is greatly influenced by the ease of finding and installing software that I enjoy, I suppose. While it is true that the absolute number of programs available for Windows is far greater than any other OS, I don't have to search Google for hours and visit multiple Warez sites to find 'em. <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="wink" smilieid="5" /><br />
<br />
I guess it doesn't help that I'm morally opposed to pirated software (can't afford it? tough... do without, or use one of the many alternatives), so I consider anything like that a non-option.</p>
	
	
	
