	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Kirec</b><br /><i>And by that I suppose you mean, "only as fast as x86 machines."</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>No, I mean not nearly as fast as x86 machines. A high end AthlonXP or low end Athlon64 will run rings around the best of them, as will a P4c 2.8 or higher. The G5 was a benchmarking joke...Apple fudged the numbers worse than I'd ever seen anybody try it, and took a page right out of "Lying with Statistics" to get their results. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Please tell me you'd like to get into a Unix vs. Windows stability argument. Please. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><hr size="1" /></blockquote>No, but MacOS (as opposed to OSX, which is an entirely different beast) vs. Windows is a nobrainer. Windows wins by a landslide.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />OS X is neither Linux, nor anything to be avoided. It's an excellent Darwin-based Unix operating system that more people should try.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>OS X / Linux / Unix = pretty much all the same stuff. Useless for the normal user, too hard to change anything/get under the hood, unless you are a coder. Windows, you don't need to be a coder, you don't need to know the code (Which is fortunate, because MS won't give it to you.) You can change anything you want with a few clicks. Yes, that means for the extremely saavy, Linux is more flexible, but that's pointless to 99% of people who are competent with computers, because they are not capable of, nor do they have any interest in, learning to work at such a low level within the OS.</p>
	
	
	
