	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>No, I mean not nearly as fast as x86 machines. A high end AthlonXP or low end Athlon64 will run rings around the best of them, as will a P4c 2.8 or higher. The G5 was a benchmarking joke...Apple fudged the numbers worse than I'd ever seen anybody try it, and took a page right out of "Lying with Statistics" to get their results.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>PPC processors are quite fast, and while Apple tends towards expensive hardware, the top-end Macs are every bit as fast as top-end x86 machines. You don't get the same performance for the dollar, but there really isn't a speed difference between the two architectures. In fact, there isn't much of a price difference, either, except that artificially imposed by Apple - I'm hoping that PPC processors make their way into alternate hardware platforms at some point so that the rest of us can benefit from additional competition in the CPU market.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>No, but MacOS (as opposed to OSX, which is an entirely different beast) vs. Windows is a nobrainer. Windows wins by a landslide.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Since OS X is the current operating system sold on Macs, you must assume that to be the OS in any comparison. If you insist on using OS 9, you should use Windows 9x as the benchmark.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Talyandrei Thistleshade</b><br /><i>OS X / Linux / Unix = pretty much all the same stuff. Useless for the normal user, too hard to change anything/get under the hood, unless you are a coder. Windows, you don't need to be a coder, you don't need to know the code (Which is fortunate, because MS won't give it to you.) You can change anything you want with a few clicks. Yes, that means for the extremely saavy, Linux is more flexible, but that's pointless to 99% of people who are competent with computers, because they are not capable of, nor do they have any interest in, learning to work at such a low level within the OS.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>You can always get a distribution that hides those things from you. OS X, Mandrake, Red Hat - all user friendly for someone who doesn't want to poke around under the hood.</p>
	
	
	
