	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Kirec</b><br /><i>Since OS X is the current operating system sold on Macs, you must assume that to be the OS in any comparison. If you insist on using OS 9, you should use Windows 9x as the benchmark.<br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I was using WindowsXP in 2001. before OS X was available. WindowsXP is just Windows2000 with a paintjob, which was out in 1999, which was a major revision from WinNT, not 9x.<br />
<br />
I'm afraid when comparing current NT Kernel OSes against Macs, OS9 is the one to compare them against. OS X is a unix competitor, not a Windows XP competitor.<br />
<br />
As for performance, here you go.<br />
<a href="http://www.pcworld.com/reviews/article/0,aid,112749,pg,8,00.asp" target="_blank">http://www.pcworld.com/reviews/arti...749,pg,8,00.asp</a><br />
<br />
<br />
As for "hiding things from the user," that's sortof my point. Windows lets you do everything Linux can do, without requiring the sort of knowledge Linux needs to poke around under the hood. In linux you can hide the options to do so, but you lose the functionality it you do. In windows, that functionality is always there.</p>
	
	
	
