<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Burlwood</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Aug 2003<br />
	Location: Southern California
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Kirec</b><br /><i>More and more, I'm finding that alternatives to Microsoft software are interesting, engaging, and fun to use....I feel quite strongly that they are starting to fall behind in a technological sense.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br />
My first computers were from RadioShack and Atari.  When I made the switch to PC's and Microsoft, I did so with the conscious knowledge that I was going backwards in terms of both "interesting, engaging, and fun to use" (I left behind color and sound, for example, and some great games) and technologically (the Amiga and Atari ST were on the market before Windows 3.1).  As a result, I have never been under the delusion that my commitment to Windows has anything to do with interesting, engaging, fun to use, technology, or cost.<br />
 <br />
Microsoft Windows' real strength--the reason I switched--was its ubiquity.  "Everyone else" was using it.  It does no good to create a business presentation that won't run on anyone else's machine.  It is useless creating a document for publication that the printer's equipment doesn't recognize.  Try getting an answer to "Hey, can anyone tell me how to make my Acme Letter Writer on my Johnny Rocket computer print in landscape mode?"<br />
 <br />
I've tried Unix, and I liked it--but I would never switch to it, because "nobody" else in my world uses it.  I've tried Macs, and didn't like them; this was no doubt because of my previous experiences with other systems: I could never seem to get a Mac program tweaked to my liking, plus everything seemed to cost three times as much as it should have.<br />
 <br />
Things are better today, compatability-wise; one can make presentations that will work with a variety of hardware platforms and using a presentation viewer utility, one can save documents in other formats and read multiple formats from the same software, and sound and video standards are widely supported. However, "better" still doesn't mean "good enough," and the pressure is always on to be compatible with the latest Microsoft incarnation.  In the meantime there is exactly one program that I need to emulate the MacOS for, but several I would need to emulate Windows for.<br />
 <br />
I have no great love for Microsoft, but I know why I switched to it, and I won't be leaving Microsoft (other than for hobby purposes) until "everyone else" does, too.  Five million flies can't be wrong!</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><font color="darkslategray"><b><font size="3"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=843807" target="_blank">Burlwood</a> </font></b><br />
<i><font size="1">Wood Elf Pathfinder 53 Drinal</font> </i></font></div>
	
	
