	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>The big problem I have with Macs is that you have to buy all their products.  I want to go and buy any part I want and stick it in a Mac like I can a PC.  They are also more expensive, and less upgradable.  If they would open it up to the market then maybe more people would buy from them.<br />
 <br />
As for Linux, the only good image editing they have is Gimp.  It's ok once I figured out how to use it, but there are lots of stuff that are far easier to do with photoshop or fireworks.  There are also much better html editors for Windows.  Plus I need something to do flash authoring, which I haven't found for linux.  I just started using MS Money also, and it's a fantastic program.  The best thing I have found for Linux is checkbook, and that program is garbage compared to the features of Quickbooks or Money.  Now that said, Open Office is nearly as good and Gaim is very nice, I even use it on Windows.  I also like how you can customize the desktop.  WindowsXP is very stable and easy to use, but Linux still has the edge.  I just want more companies to make software for Linux, while open source projects are nice, many times the paid software is just a lot better.  I don't mind paying for software if it's good stuff.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />"The fish, they dishonor me." - The Samurai Sportsman</div>
	
	
